# linux-bioinformatics-toolkit

Command-line utilities and automation scripts for handling biological
sequence data, built while applying Linux/Bash fundamentals (LFS101x)
to real bioinformatics file-processing tasks.

## Scripts

| Script | Purpose | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `fastq_organizer.sh` | Batch-renames/organizes FASTQ files by sample ID | `./scripts/fastq_organizer.sh data/` |
| `fasta_stats.sh` | Sequence count, length distribution, GC% from FASTA | `./scripts/fasta_stats.sh genome.fasta` |
| `fetch_public_data.sh` | Downloads + checksum-verifies public SRA/GEO data | `./scripts/fetch_public_data.sh SRR000001` |
| `job_watchdog.sh` | Monitors a long-running job, logs CPU/mem, restarts on failure | `./scripts/job_watchdog.sh <pid>` |
| `log_report.sh` | Parses pipeline logs into a Markdown summary | `./scripts/log_report.sh logs/` |
| `env_setup.sh` | Reproducible conda environment bootstrap | `./scripts/env_setup.sh` |
| `qc_pipeline.sh` | End-to-end fetch -> organize -> stats -> report pipeline | `./scripts/qc_pipeline.sh config.txt` |
| `batch_parallel_report.sh` | Parallel multi-sample processing + aggregated report | `./scripts/batch_parallel_report.sh samples/` |

## Requirements

- Bash 5+, GNU coreutils (Ubuntu 22.04 / WSL2)
- `wget`, `awk`, `sed`, `shellcheck` (for CI)

## Usage

See individual script headers, or `docs/usage.md` for worked examples.

## Security notes

Scripts default to least-privilege: no unnecessary `sudo`, downloaded
files are checksum-verified before use, and permissions on any
generated data are set explicitly rather than inherited.

